One piece of advice that I received that helped me a lot in [REDACTED] “Don’t teach me, just convince me.” A listener can assess for level of understanding/medical knowledge in a presentation or a note by simply seeing what evidence was used to support the proposed decisions. For example, for a patient [REDACTED] [REDACTED]’s, you [REDACTED] need to talk through the results of a dexamethasone suppression test or, in [REDACTED] [REDACTED] need to “teach” the listener [REDACTED] interpret the test. Thus, in [REDACTED] you would report the test value and [REDACTED][REDACTED] plan you could say something like “cortisol appropriately suppressed with dexamethasone, making [REDACTED]’s syndrome much less likely”. In [REDACTED] listener will know that you understand how the test works[REDACTED] appropriately interpret the values. This example leaves out the extra words that many people would naturally want to say during a presentation (including myself!) that end up “teaching” the listener like “Since cortisone naturally peaks [REDACTED][REDACTED][REDACTED], a low AM cortisol level after a dexamethasone dose shows that cortisol production was suppressed by the dexamethasone. This would be expected [REDACTED][REDACTED] hormonal axis. Since we did the test to look for [REDACTED]’s … etc etc”. If you worry about being too brief with this approach, remember that he listener or note reader can always ask for more clarification on your though process if they want/need it. The best time to really spell out your thoughts during a presentation or a note is when you are breaking from [REDACTED] or doing something more unconventional. For example, give a full sentence as to why a person [REDACTED][REDACTED] on goal directed medical therapy (allergies, didn’t tolerate the side effects, etc), or why are you choosing a non standard antibiotic regimen (multiple recent hospitalizations at [REDACTED] of growing a really resistant bug) or why a patient [REDACTED] cough doesn’t have a CXR (scared of the X ray machine and refuses, cannot be properly positioned).
